SIMPLE: flatulent
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Flatulent
<hw>Flat"u*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>flatus</ets> a blowing, <ets>flatus ventris</ets> windiness,
flatulence, fr. <ets>flare</ets> to blow: cf. F. <ets>flatulent</ets>.
See <er>Blow</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Affected with flatus{2} or
gases generated in the alimentary canal; windy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Generating, or tending to generate, wind in the
stomach.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Vegetables abound more with a⟦eum⟧rial particles than animal
substances, and therefore are more <qex>flatulent</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Turgid with flatus; <as>as, a <ex>flatulent</ex>
tumor</as>.</def> <rj><au>Quincy.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Pretentious without substance or reality; puffy;
empty; vain; <as>as, a <ex>flatulent</ex> vanity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is too <qex>flatulent</qex> sometimes, and sometimes too
dry.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flatulently</ent>⟦br⟧
